poem:
Beware the Agenda-Gnash

At noonish hush the glazegloom grew—tick-tock—a tempered doom,
Beware the Agenda-Gnash, my crew; its charts will chomp and chase;
Beware the splay of swivel-sway, the plug-vine tangle-bloom,
And shun the buzz-buzz bindersnap that snaps across your space.

He primed his pointer-saber—click!—for brisk agenda-solve;
Strapped on a notepad buckler bold, a lanyard-loop cuirass;
With coffee-crackle courage quick, his focus firmed resolve;
He paced the projector-prairie pale, past panes of panel-glass.

Out from the quartzwhite screen it slid—whirr, clack—an office drawl;
The Agenda-Gnash with piechart jaws and spreadsheet-scything stare;
Its laser-lash and pointer-poke went ping-pang, primed to maul;
While memodust and marker-mist made migraine-colored glare.

I raised the clicker-scythe and leapt—ka-CHAK!—through swivel-thud;
We grappled in clatter-cascade storm, in knotted cable-snare;
I cleft its gantt-gullet clean in twain; out poured a graphy flood;
Then stillness settled, soft as slides, unspooling from the snare.

Now noonish hush in glazeglow gleams; tick-tock turns tame the room;
We jingled cupclink-chorus bright and stapled smiles in place;
No swivel-sway nor plug-vine snarl; fresh flipcharts fizz and bloom;
All hail the minutes, mended neat; hooray for homely grace.

Where once the glazegloom grew and tick-tock tolled of doom,
No more the Agenda-Gnash shall gnaw nor shadow meeting space;
Now giggle-light and stapler-sunbeam brim the braveboard room;
So share the snap of snacktime cheer and set a kinder pace.
